In this report, we implemented data analysis with some visualizations and adressed a classification problem. The dataset we used is collected from the kaggle website. It is a dataset of every fatal shooting in the United States by a police officer. We have framed different research questions for understanding the dataset and uncovering the hidden patterns, meaningful insights from the dataset.

The FBI and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention log fatal shootings by police, but officials acknowledge that their data is incomplete. In 2015, The Post documented more than two times more fatal shootings by police than had been recorded by the FBI. Last year, the FBI announced plans to overhaul how it tracks fatal police encounters. All the information of the fatal shooting from 2015 to 2020 in present in the dataset we have used.

The objective of this report is to analyze the fatal shooting data in order to get some useful insights. We have implemented exploratory data analysis to get better understanding of the dataset, data cleaning as the data contains a lot of missing values and we cannot simply drop those rows having missing values. It also contains some inappropriate values that we have handled accordingle. Some columns like race and armed contains a lot of categories so we have replaced them with the 0 and 1 for white and not white and armed and unarmed respectively. After that, we have build a lot of visualizations that will address some of the research questions.

Dataset Description¶

The dataset includes data based on the demographics of police-initiated fatal shootings in the United States. It comprises 14 columns and 5416 records for deadly shootings. The following columns are present:

  • id
  • name
  • date
  • manner_of_death
  • armed
  • age
  • gender
  • race
  • city
  • state
  • signs_of_mental_illness
  • threat_level
  • flee
  • body_camera

As you may see from the output result, the columns armed, age, gender, race, and body camera all have blank values. We must now respond appropriately to these missing values.

We can just substitute unavailable data for the missing values in the armed and race columns. We can use the age that appears most frequently in the dataset to fill the values in the age column. There are only two rows in the gender column that have null values, therefore we can easily remove those rows. For flee, we can replace missing values with others.

In [ ]:
df["Armed"].fillna("Data not available", inplace = True)
df["Age"].fillna(df["Age"].mode()[0], inplace = True)
df["Race"].fillna("Data not available", inplace = True)
df['Flee'].fillna("Other",inplace = True)
In [ ]:
# drop the remaining rows with nan values
df.dropna(inplace = True)

        armed_list.append('unarmed')

df['Armed'] = armed_list

Research Question: Does the data on fatal shootings in the United States reveal any discernible patterns or variations in the number of incidents based on factors such as gender, manner of death, and the presence of mental illness?

The insights that can be drawn from the above bar charts are:

1. Number of deaths based on the manner of death: There are a lot of persons who got died due to shot and a very less number of person who got died due to shot and tasered.

2. Number of deaths based on the gender: It can be clearly visible that males are the one who got died mostly.

3. Number of deaths based on the race: The number of white people died is more than any other race community.

4. Number of deaths based on signs of mental illness: The number of person who got died in fatal shooting not suffering from any kind of mental illness is more compared to the person who is suffering from that.

5. Number of deaths based on flee category: There are a lot of persons died that did not flee.

6. Number of deaths based on body camera: Number of persons got died is more who does not have a body camera.

As we can see, shootings account for the majority of the incidents. Tasering is typically a challenging procedure that requires the officers to be dangerously near to potentially armed suspects. As a result, officers typically choose to use force to neutralise threats.

Year 2015:

Month 7 witnessed the highest number of fatal shootings, with a count of 100.

Year 2019:

Month 12 also recorded the highest number of fatal shootings, matching the count of 100.

Yearly Breakdown:

In 2015, fatal shootings peaked in July with a count of 100. In 2016, the highest monthly count was 90 in March. In 2017, February had the highest count at 97. In 2018, March saw the highest count of fatal shootings, totaling 99.

Lowest Counts: The lowest count across all years occurred in 2017, with December recording the least number of fatal shootings, totaling 39.

Potential Trends and Patterns:

  • A general finding indicates that December often has comparatively less counts in a number of years (2015, 2016, 2017).

  • Although July (100) had a peak in fatal shootings in both 2015 and 2019, there is no discernible pattern for the exact months with the highest numbers of shootings in any given year.

  • It's important to remember that annual variations in fatal shooting counts imply that patterns or trends could be impacted by a range of circumstances and are not always in line. Additional examination may investigate the contributing elements behind these discrepancies.

Research Question: What is the maximum percentage of shootings recorded within a particular age group?

In [ ]:
# Converting the ages number to the age groups
age_list = []
for i in df['Age']:
    if 0<i<15:
        age_list.append("0-15")
    if 15<=i<25:
        age_list.append("15-25")
    if 25<=i<35:
        age_list.append("25-35")
    if 35<=i<45:
        age_list.append("35-45")
    if 45<=i<55:
        age_list.append("45-55")
    if i>=55:
        age_list.append("more than 55")
df['Age Group'] = age_list

The information makes us think about how people's living situations—whether they are in cities or rural areas—and their economic circumstances affect these trends. It also begs the question of how law enforcement deals with various age groups.

The provided data outlines the count of individuals who tragically lost their lives due to fatal shootings in the United States, categorized by race (0 representing non-whites and 1 representing whites) across different years.

Yearly Overview:

In 2015, there were 468 fatal shootings involving non-white individuals (Race Category 0) and 497 involving white individuals (Race Category 1). The trend continued in subsequent years, with fluctuations in counts but consistently higher incidents involving non-white individuals compared to white individuals.

Overall Patterns:

Across the years, non-white individuals consistently experienced a higher number of fatal shootings compared to white individuals. The data suggests variations in counts between the two racial categories, emphasizing the need for a nuanced examination of contributing factors.

2019 Anomaly:

In 2019, there was a reversal in the trend, with 454 fatal shootings involving non-white individuals and 404 involving white individuals. This anomaly merits further investigation to understand the factors contributing to the shift in counts.

Insights for different age group and race:

  • Racial differences in fatal shootings occur across age groups, highlighting the need for a sophisticated understanding and treatment of underlying causes.
  • Across all age groups, the number of fatal shootings involving Black individuals is continuously greater, which has prompted a closer look at socioeconomic and law enforcement issues.
  • Notable events involving Hispanic people highlight how important it is to take a variety of racial demographics into account when talking about fatal shootings.
  • The distribution of fatal occurrences by age and race emphasises the need for focused interventions and policy thinking to address root causes and advance fair results.

This graph also demonstrates the police's objectivity in that it depicts how they have handled every danger equally, regardless of ethnicity.

Conclusion¶

The data on fatal shootings in the US provides insights into intricate patterns that call for a sophisticated comprehension of interactions between law enforcement. Disparities have been observed among demographic parameters, including age, gender, race, and kind of flee, which may provide insights into regions that could benefit from focused interventions. Younger people are more likely to be fatally shot than older people, especially those in the 25–35 age range. This highlights the necessity for law enforcement procedures to take this into account. Given the gender gap, which results in men making up the great majority of offenders, it is unclear if non-lethal alternatives can effectively address female offenders. Racial inequities continue to exist, with Black people systematically having a greater number of fatal shootings in a variety of age categories. The insights regarding flee types highlight particular difficulties related to car-based gunfire and foot pursuits. It is important to approach the data cautiously and acknowledge the complex interplay of factors impacting deadly shootings even as we acknowledge these tendencies. The tendencies that have been noted call for continued study and policy discussions in order to advance fair and community-focused law enforcement methods that will ultimately result in safer results for all parties.
